hould make Expressly not part of the main implementation. Instead, it could be under testImplementation, which includes it in the native test classpath. If the HV classloader likely includes all dependencies from the system app classloader, that seems like a successful path. However, maybe the current build still has the old jakarta.el as testRuntimeOnly, which could create a conflict. The preflight indicates Expressly is applied, but the old dependency may still linger. That’s a bit tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning test class development**\\n\\nI need to create a dedicated test class for the ResourceBundleMessageInterpolator, likely without an existing one. I’m considering whether to package it outside the library, maybe under org.graalvm.reachability or use com.example.hibernatevalidator. Tests can probably be in the default package, but they need to be top-level public. I should also explore the dynamic-access report after running but need to understand how to construct the ResourceBundleMessageInterpolator directly in the test. I’ll look into source documentation for OSGi.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_HUNvqSm3hiRWLxjDtyLaDVvI|fc_07128e2cacf06c13016a3bf2f5ec908193bded7d357196bee2", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"classLoaderForExpressionFactory\\|ResourceBundleMessageInterpolator\" -n /home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.hibernate.validator/hibernate-validator/9.1.0.Final/main/extracted | head -50"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2673, "output": 702, "cacheRead": 17408, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 20783, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782313703497, "responseId": "resp_07128e2cacf06c13016a3bf2e8201481939e2bc3fe5c7456b6"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_HUNvqSm3hiRWLxjDtyLaD