[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring OSGi testing issues**\n\nI’m considering the source_context and whether it includes tests, but it seems to need no compile/run. Maybe I could write a test with a minimal ClassLoader that overrides loadClass for OSGi classes. However, I won’t create stubs or fake replacements for library API types. It seems I need an actual OSGi API dependency, like adding testImplementation for org.osgi.core. But FrameworkUtil.getBundle might return null unless loaded by an OSGi bundle classloader, so maybe I should explore Apache Felix?\n\n**Addressing classloading issues**\n\nI’m running into challenges with the ResourceBundleMessageInterpolator class. FrameworkUtil.getBundle returns null unless it's loaded from a bundle, which means I need OSGi classloading for the HV classes during runtime. The rules say not to create tests that introduce new classes, especially for custom class loaders. So, it seems OSGi fallbacks are unsupported by these rules. I wonder if there's a way to reach `classLoaderForExpressionFactory` even with currentBundle being null. Maybe using a child ClassLoader for test nested static classes could work, provided they don't introduce new org.osgi classes.\n\n**Exploring OSGi framework options**\n\nI’m considering generating byte arrays or defining classes at runtime, but that seems to be prohibited. Also, source stubs in the org.osgi package aren’t allowed. One idea could be adding a dependency for actual OSGi and running Felix. That might allow me to load HV into the OSGi framework. It's a thought worth exploring since it could help me work around the restrictions I'm facing! I'll need to test this approach further.\n\n**Writing test for message interpolator**\n\nI need to write a test for the ResourceBundleMessageInterpolator. There are existing tests in the org.hibernate.validator package, but the rules specify that I should keep the dynami